    public TokenBuffer deserialize(JsonParser jp, DeserializationContext ctxt) throws IOException
    {
        JsonToken t = jp.getCurrentToken();
        if (t == JsonToken.FIELD_NAME) {
            // 28-Oct-2014, tatu: As per #592, need to support a special case of starting from
            //    FIELD_NAME, which is taken to mean that we are missing START_OBJECT, but need
            //    to assume one did exist.
            writeStartObject();
            do {
                copyCurrentStructure(jp);
                t = jp.getCurrentToken();
            } while (t == JsonToken.FIELD_NAME);
            // now t should be END_OBJECT, copy it as well
            copyCurrentStructure(jp);
        } else {
            copyCurrentStructure(jp);
        }
        return this;
    }

But note: after the loop, we call copyCurrentStructure(jp) again. However, after the loop, t is the token after the last field's value, which should be END_OBJECT. But we have already obtained t from jp.getCurrentToken() in the while condition. When the loop exits, t is not FIELD_NAME, so we have already read the token (END_OBJECT) but we haven't copied it. So we should copy it. However, we need to be careful: the while condition checks t == JsonToken.FIELD_NAME. If t is END_OBJECT, the loop exits, and t holds END_OBJECT. Then we call copyCurrentStructure(jp) which will copy the END_OBJECT token. That's fine.

